[0m[49m[39m  130, 130[0m:[39m[49m     style D fill:#f9f,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[39m  131, 131[0m:[39m[49m     style G fill:#9ff,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[39m  132, 132[0m:[39m[49m     style H fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[39m  133, 133[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  134, 134[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  135, 135[0m:[39m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[39m  136, 136[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  137, 137[0m:[39m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[39m  138, 138[0m:[39m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[39m  139, 139[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon Comprehend, Comprehend Medical, S3, Lambda, DynamoDB, QuickSight, EventBridge, SNS |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 140     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `comprehend:DetectSentiment`, `comprehend:ClassifyDocument`, `comprehend:DetectPiiEntities`, `comprehendmedical:DetectPHI`, `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:Query` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | Each Lambda function needs its own execution role scoped to minimum resources. PHI-detection Lambda: `comprehendmedical:DetectPHI`, `s3:GetObject` on `feedback-raw/*`, `s3:PutObject` on `feedback-redacted/*`. Sentiment Lambda: `comprehend:DetectSentiment`, `s3:GetObject` on `feedback-redacted/*`. Aspect Lambda: `comprehend:ClassifyDocument`, `dynamodb:PutItem` on `sentiment-results` table ARN, `events:PutEvents`. The PHI boundary between raw and redacted buckets is the core security control; IAM must enforce it. |
[0m[49m[39m  141, 141[0m:[39m[49m | **BAA** | Required: patient feedback often contains PHI (names, dates, diagnoses mentioned in free text) |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 142     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **Encryption** | S3: SSE-KMS; DynamoDB: encryption at rest (default); Lambda logs: KMS-encrypted CloudWatch log groups; all API calls over TLS |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 143     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **VPC** | Production: Lambda in VPC with VPC endpoints for S3, Comprehend, DynamoDB, and CloudWatch Logs |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Encryption** | S3: SSE-KMS with customer-managed key; DynamoDB: encryption at rest (default, verify enabled); Lambda logs: KMS-encrypted CloudWatch log groups; all API calls over TLS |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **VPC** | Production: Lambda in VPC with VPC endpoints for S3 (gateway), DynamoDB (gateway), Comprehend (interface), Comprehend Medical (interface, separate from Comprehend), and CloudWatch Logs (interface). Note: EventBridge does not have a VPC endpoint; the alerting Lambda requires NAT Gateway connectivity or should write alert records to DynamoDB for a non-VPC Lambda to forward. |
[0m[49m[39m  144, 144[0m:[39m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled: log all Comprehend and S3 API calls for audit trail |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Data Retention** | Configure S3 lifecycle rules on `feedback-raw/` (contains PHI): transition to Glacier after 30 days, expire per your organization's retention policy (typically 6-7 years for non-clinical operational data, verify with compliance). Enable S3 Object Lock if regulatory hold is required. The `feedback-redacted/` bucket has lower sensitivity but should still have a defined lifecycle. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Training Data** | Custom aspect classifier requires minimum 200 labeled examples per aspect category (10 categories = 2,000+ examples). Format: CSV with text and category columns per Comprehend Custom Classification requirements. Training time: 30-60 minutes. Budget 2-4 weeks for initial labeling by patient experience staff who understand both the aspect taxonomy and clinical context. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Error Handling** | Configure SQS dead-letter queues on each Lambda function. Failed items route to DLQ for investigation and replay. CloudWatch alarm on DLQ message count > 0 alerts operations. Systematic failures (new feedback format causing parse errors) can silently drop thousands of items, creating misleading aggregate trends. |
[0m[49m[39m  145, 148[0m:[39m[49m | **Sample Data** | Synthetic patient feedback. CMS publishes [HCAHPS survey results](https://data.cms.gov/provider-data/topics/hospitals/overall-hospital-quality-star-rating) (aggregate only). Generate synthetic verbatim comments for development. Never use real patient feedback in non-production environments without proper de-identification. |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 146     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | Comprehend DetectSentiment: $0.0001 per unit (100 chars). For average 500-char feedback: ~$0.0005/item. PHI detection adds ~$0.01/item. Custom classification: $0.0005/item. At 50,000 items/month: ~$550/month total. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | Comprehend DetectSentiment: $0.0001 per unit (100 chars). For average 500-char feedback: ~$0.0005/item. PHI detection adds ~$0.01/item. Custom classification: $0.0005/item. Custom classification endpoint hosting: $0.50/hour per inference unit ($360/month minimum, always-on). At 50,000 items/month: ~$910/month total (including endpoint). For batch processing (non-real-time), use Comprehend async classification jobs instead of a real-time endpoint to eliminate hosting cost. |
[0m[49m[39m  147, 150[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  148, 151[0m:[39m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[39m  149, 152[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  150, 153[0m:[39m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[39m  151, 154[0m:[39m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[39m  152, 155[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon Comprehend** | Sentiment detection (built-in) and custom aspect classification |
[0m[49m[39m  153, 156[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon Comprehend Medical** | PHI entity detection for preprocessing/redaction |
[0m[49m[39m  154, 157[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Raw and redacted feedback storage; organized by source and date |
[0m[49m[39m  155, 158[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | Orchestration: PHI detection, sentiment analysis, aspect extraction, result assembly |
[0m[49m[39m  156, 159[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Stores analyzed results for dashboard queries and trend detection |
[0m[49m[39m  157, 160[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon QuickSight** | Patient experience dashboards and visualizations |
[0m[49m[39m  158, 161[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon EventBridge** | Routes trend alerts to appropriate teams |
[0m[49m[39m  159, 162[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Encryption key management for all PHI-containing resources |
[0m[49m[39m  160, 163[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Metrics, logs, and alarms for pipeline health |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon SQS** | Dead-letter queues for failed processing items |
[0m[49m[39m  161, 165[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  162, 166[0m:[39m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[39m  163, 167[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  164, 168[0m:[39m[49m > **Reference implementations:** The following AWS sample repos demonstrate patterns used in this recipe:
[0m[49m[39m  165, 169[0m:[39m[49m >
[0m[49m[39m  166, 170[0m:[39m[49m > - [`amazon-comprehend-examples`](https://github.com/aws-samples/amazon-comprehend-examples): General Comprehend examples including sentiment analysis, custom classification, and entity detection
[0m[49m[39m  167, 171[0m:[39m[49m > - [`amazon-comprehend-medical-fhir-integration`](https://github.com/aws-samples/amazon-comprehend-medical-fhir-integration): Healthcare-specific: integrating Comprehend Medical with FHIR for clinical NLP pipelines
[0m[49m[39m  168, 172[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  169, 173[0m:[39m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[39m  170, 174[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  171, 175[0m:[39m[49m **Step 1: PHI detection and redaction.** Before any analysis, the system scans incoming feedback for protected health information. Patient comments routinely mention provider names, specific diagnoses, medication names, and dates of service. The PHI detection pass identifies these entities and either redacts them (replaces with placeholder tokens like `[PROVIDER_NAME]`) or tags them for downstream handling. This step is non-negotiable for any pipeline processing patient-generated text. The redacted version is what flows to sentiment analysis, so your sentiment models never need access to identifiable information. Skip this step and you're running PHI through analytics services without proper safeguards.
[0m[49m[39m  172, 176[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  173, 177[0m:[39m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[39m  174, 178[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION detect_and_redact_phi(feedback_text):
[0m[49m[39m  175, 179[0m:[39m[49m     // Call the medical NLP service to identify any PHI in the text.
[0m[49m[39m  176, 180[0m:[39m[49m     // PHI includes: names, dates, phone numbers, medical record numbers,
[0m[49m[39m  177, 181[0m:[39m[49m     // and any other individually identifiable health information.
[0m[49m[39m  178, 182[0m:[39m[49m     phi_entities = call ComprehendMedical.DetectPHI with:
[0m[49m[39m  179, 183[0m:[39m[49m         text = feedback_text
[0m[49m[39m  180, 184[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  181, 185[0m:[39m[49m     // Build the redacted version by replacing each detected entity with a placeholder.
[0m[49m[39m  182, 186[0m:[39m[49m     // We preserve the entity type so downstream analysis knows a provider was mentioned
[0m[49m[39m  183, 187[0m:[39m[49m     // even though we've removed the actual name.
[0m[49m[39m  184, 188[0m:[39m[49m     redacted_text = feedback_text
[0m[49m[39m  185, 189[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each entity in phi_entities (sorted by offset, descending):
[0m[49m[39m  186, 190[0m:[39m[49m         // Replace from back to front so character offsets remain valid.
[0m[49m[39m  187, 191[0m:[39m[49m         // Example: "Dr. Smith was kind" becomes "[PROVIDER_NAME] was kind"
[0m[49m[39m  188, 192[0m:[39m[49m         redacted_text = replace characters at entity.BeginOffset..entity.EndOffset
[0m[49m[39m  189, 193[0m:[39m[49m                         with "[" + entity.Type + "]"
[0m[49m[39m  190, 194[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  191, 195[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN {
[0m[49m[39m  192, 196[0m:[39m[49m         redacted_text: redacted_text,      // safe for downstream analytics
[0m[49m[39m  193, 197[0m:[39m[49m         phi_detected: length(phi_entities) > 0,  // flag for audit
[0m[49m[39m  194, 198[0m:[39m[49m         entity_count: length(phi_entities)
[0m[49m[39m  195, 199[0m:[39m[49m     }
[0m[49m[39m  196, 200[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  197, 201[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  198, 202[0m:[39m[49m **Step 2: Sentiment analysis.** The redacted text goes to the sentiment analysis service. This returns an overall sentiment label (POSITIVE, NEGATIVE, NEUTRAL, MIXED) along with confidence scores for each category. The confidence distribution is often more informative than the top label. A comment scored 60% negative and 35% positive is qualitatively different from one scored 95% negative. The MIXED category is especially important in healthcare feedback, where patients commonly express both gratitude and frustration in the same response. Store the full score distribution, not just the winning label.
[0m[49m[39m  199, 203[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  200, 204[0m:[39m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[39m  201, 205[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION analyze_sentiment(redacted_text):
[0m[49m[39m  202, 206[0m:[39m[49m     // Call the sentiment detection service.
[0m[49m[39m  203, 207[0m:[39m[49m     // Input must be under 5,000 bytes (UTF-8). Patient feedback typically fits easily.
[0m[49m[39m  204, 208[0m:[39m[49m     // For longer texts (call transcripts), split into paragraphs and analyze each.
[0m[49m[39m  205, 209[0m:[39m[49m     response = call Comprehend.DetectSentiment with:
[0m[49m[39m  206, 210[0m:[39m[49m         text          = redacted_text
[0m[49m[39m  207, 211[0m:[39m[49m         language_code = "en"    // detect language first for multilingual populations
[0m[49m[39m  208, 212[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  209, 213[0m:[39m[49m     // Extract the full score distribution, not just the top label.
[0m[49m[39m  210, 214[0m:[39m[49m     // A 55% negative / 40% positive split tells a different story than 95% negative.
[0m[49m[39m  211, 215[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN {
[0m[49m[39m  212, 216[0m:[39m[49m         sentiment: response.Sentiment,           // "POSITIVE", "NEGATIVE", "NEUTRAL", "MIXED"
[0m[49m[39m  213, 217[0m:[39m[49m         scores: {
[0m[49m[39m  214, 218[0m:[39m[49m             positive: response.SentimentScore.Positive,
[0m[49m[39m  215, 219[0m:[39m[49m             negative: response.SentimentScore.Negative,
[0m[49m[39m  216, 220[0m:[39m[49m             neutral: response.SentimentScore.Neutral,
[0m[49m[39m  217, 221[0m:[39m[49m             mixed: response.SentimentScore.Mixed
[0m[49m[39m  218, 222[0m:[39m[49m         },
[0m[49m[39m  219, 223[0m:[39m[49m         confidence: maximum of all four scores    // how decisive the classification is
[0m[49m[39m  220, 224[0m:[39m[49m     }
[0m[49m[39m  221, 225[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  222, 226[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  223, 227[0m:[39m[49m **Step 3: Aspect extraction.** This is where generic sentiment becomes actionable intelligence. The system classifies which aspect(s) of the healthcare experience are mentioned in each piece of feedback. A custom classifier trained on your labeled data maps text segments to your aspect taxonomy. For each detected aspect, the system also captures the sentiment directed specifically at that aspect. One comment might yield: `{wait_time: NEGATIVE, provider_quality: POSITIVE, facility: NEUTRAL}`. That's three distinct operational signals from one piece of text.
[0m[49m[39m  224, 228[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  225, 229[0m:[39m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[39m  226, 230[0m:[39m[49m // The aspect taxonomy reflects what patient experience teams actually care about.
[0m[49m[39m  227, 231[0m:[39m[49m // This should be configured, not hardcoded. Add/remove aspects as your organization evolves.
[0m[49m[39m  228, 232[0m:[39m[49m ASPECT_TAXONOMY = [
[0m[49m[39m  229, 233[0m:[39m[49m     "wait_time",              // scheduling delays, in-office wait
[0m[49m[39m  230, 234[0m:[39m[49m     "provider_communication", // bedside manner, explanations, listening
[0m[49m[39m  231, 235[0m:[39m[49m     "staff_interaction",      // nursing, front desk, technicians
[0m[49m[39m  232, 236[0m:[39m[49m     "facility_environment",   // cleanliness, comfort, noise, parking
[0m[49m[39m  233, 237[0m:[39m[49m     "billing_insurance",      // charges, statements, coverage confusion
[0m[49m[39m  234, 238[0m:[39m[49m     "care_coordination",      // referrals, follow-up, transitions
[0m[49m[39m  235, 239[0m:[39m[49m     "pain_management",        // pain control, medication responsiveness
[0m[49m[39m  236, 240[0m:[39m[49m     "discharge_process",      // instructions, timing, readiness
[0m[49m[39m  237, 241[0m:[39m[49m     "access_convenience",     // hours, location, telehealth availability
[0m[49m[39m  238, 242[0m:[39m[49m     "overall_experience"      // general impressions not tied to specific aspect
[0m[49m[39m  239, 243[0m:[39m[49m ]
[0m[49m[39m  240, 244[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  241, 245[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION extract_aspects(redacted_text, document_sentiment):
[0m[49m[39m  242, 246[0m:[39m[49m     // Split text into sentences for finer-grained analysis.
[0m[49m[39m  243, 247[0m:[39m[49m     // A single feedback item often covers multiple aspects across sentences.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // NOTE: Use a proper sentence tokenizer (like spaCy's sentencizer or NLTK's
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      249[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Punkt) that handles abbreviations (Dr., dept., etc.). Simple period-splitting
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      250[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // will break on these. For very short feedback (< 2 sentences), classify the
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // entire text as one unit rather than splitting.
[0m[49m[39m  244, 252[0m:[39m[49m     sentences = split_into_sentences(redacted_text)
[0m[49m[39m  245, 253[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  246, 254[0m:[39m[49m     aspect_results = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  247, 255[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  248, 256[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each sentence in sentences:
[0m[49m[39m  249, 257[0m:[39m[49m         // Classify which aspect this sentence is about.
[0m[49m[39m  250, 258[0m:[39m[49m         // Uses a custom classifier trained on labeled healthcare feedback.
[0m[49m[39m  251, 259[0m:[39m[49m         aspect_response = call Comprehend.ClassifyDocument with:
[0m[49m[39m  252, 260[0m:[39m[49m             text             = sentence
[0m[49m[39m  253, 261[0m:[39m[49m             endpoint_arn     = ASPECT_CLASSIFIER_ENDPOINT
[0m[49m[39m  254, 262[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  255, 263[0m:[39m[49m         // Get the top aspect prediction with confidence.
[0m[49m[39m  256, 264[0m:[39m[49m         top_aspect     = aspect_response.Classes[0].Name
[0m[49m[39m  257, 265[0m:[39m[49m         aspect_conf    = aspect_response.Classes[0].Score
[0m[49m[39m  258, 266[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  259, 267[0m:[39m[49m         // Only accept aspect classification if confidence is above threshold.
[0m[49m[39m  260, 268[0m:[39m[49m         // Low-confidence aspect assignments add noise to dashboards.
[0m[49m[39m  261, 269[0m:[39m[49m         IF aspect_conf >= 0.6:
[0m[49m[39m  262, 270[0m:[39m[49m             // Get sentence-level sentiment for this specific aspect mention.
[0m[49m[39m  263, 271[0m:[39m[49m             sentence_sentiment = call Comprehend.DetectSentiment with:
[0m[49m[39m  264, 272[0m:[39m[49m                 text          = sentence
[0m[49m[39m  265, 273[0m:[39m[49m                 language_code = "en"
[0m[49m[39m  266, 274[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  267, 275[0m:[39m[49m             append to aspect_results: {
[0m[49m[39m  268, 276[0m:[39m[49m                 aspect: top_aspect,
[0m[49m[39m  269, 277[0m:[39m[49m                 sentiment: sentence_sentiment.Sentiment,
[0m[49m[39m  270, 278[0m:[39m[49m                 confidence: aspect_conf,
[0m[49m[39m  271, 279[0m:[39m[49m                 text: sentence   // keep the source text for drill-down
[0m[49m[39m  272, 280[0m:[39m[49m             }
[0m[49m[39m  273, 281[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  274, 282[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN aspect_results
[0m[49m[39m  275, 283[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  276, 284[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  277, 285[0m:[39m[49m **Step 4: Result assembly and storage.** The final step combines all analysis outputs into a single record and writes it to the database. Each record links back to the source feedback item and includes the full analysis: document-level sentiment, aspect-level sentiments, metadata about the source channel and department, and processing timestamps. The table design supports the queries that dashboards need: filter by date range, department, sentiment, or aspect. The `needs_attention` flag routes significantly negative items to immediate human review rather than waiting for monthly reports.
[0m[49m[39m  278, 286[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  279, 287[0m:[39m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[39m  280, 288[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION store_analysis_result(source_metadata, sentiment, aspects):
[0m[49m[39m  281, 289[0m:[39m[49m     // Determine if this item needs immediate human attention.
[0m[49m[39m  282, 290[0m:[39m[49m     // Threshold: overall negative sentiment with high confidence,
[0m[49m[39m  283, 291[0m:[39m[49m     // or any critical aspect (safety, pain) with negative sentiment.
[0m[49m[39m  284, 292[0m:[39m[49m     needs_attention = (
[0m[49m[39m  285, 293[0m:[39m[49m         sentiment.sentiment == "NEGATIVE" AND sentiment.confidence >= 0.85
[0m[49m[39m  286, 294[0m:[39m[49m     ) OR any aspect in aspects where (
[0m[49m[39m  287, 295[0m:[39m[49m         aspect.aspect in ["pain_management", "care_coordination"]
[0m[49m[39m  288, 296[0m:[39m[49m         AND aspect.sentiment == "NEGATIVE"
[0m[49m[39m  289, 297[0m:[39m[49m     )
[0m[49m[39m  290, 298[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  291, 299[0m:[39m[49m     // Write the complete analysis record.
[0m[49m[39m  292, 300[0m:[39m[49m     write record to database table "sentiment-results":
[0m[49m[39m  293, 301[0m:[39m[49m         feedback_id       = source_metadata.id                    // links to original feedback
[0m[49m[39m  294, 302[0m:[39m[49m         source_channel    = source_metadata.channel               // "survey", "portal", "review", "call"
[0m[49m[39m  295, 303[0m:[39m[49m         department        = source_metadata.department            // for departmental filtering
[0m[49m[39m  296, 304[0m:[39m[49m         facility          = source_metadata.facility              // for multi-site systems
[0m[49m[39m  297, 305[0m:[39m[49m         analysis_date     = current UTC timestamp (ISO 8601)
[0m[49m[39m  298, 306[0m:[39m[49m         document_sentiment = sentiment                            // full score distribution
[0m[49m[39m  299, 307[0m:[39m[49m         aspects           = aspects                               // list of aspect-sentiment pairs
[0m[49m[39m  300, 308[0m:[39m[49m         needs_attention   = needs_attention                       // routes to review queue
[0m[49m[39m  301, 309[0m:[39m[49m         feedback_date     = source_metadata.submitted_date        // when patient submitted
[0m[49m[39m  302, 310[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  303, 311[0m:[39m[49m     // If needs_attention, also emit an event for real-time alerting.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      312[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // IMPORTANT: Do not include feedback text in the event payload. The alert
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      313[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // routes to external systems (Slack, PagerDuty) that may not be BAA-covered.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      314[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Include only the feedback_id so reviewers can look up the full text through
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      315[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // the authorized dashboard.
[0m[49m[39m  304, 316[0m:[39m[49m     IF needs_attention:
[0m[49m[39m  305, 317[0m:[39m[49m         emit event to EventBridge:
[0m[49m[39m  306, 318[0m:[39m[49m             source     = "patient-sentiment-pipeline"
[0m[49m[39m  307, 319[0m:[39m[49m             detail_type = "NegativeSentimentAlert"
[0m[49m[39m  308, 320[0m:[39m[49m             detail     = { feedback_id, department, facility, top_negative_aspect }
[0m[49m[39m  309, 321[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  310, 322[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  311, 323[0m:[39m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter08.02-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
